+# Codex Ratchet / ClaimGate Bridge Contract
+
+## Purpose
+
+Codex Ratchet is the research and gate-mining side of the same Lev project
+harness. It can mine axioms, constraints, gates, attractor-basin maps, and
+candidate repairs. It does not create a second admission authority.
+
+The bridge contract is:
+
+```text
+source pattern / research branch
+  -> axiom, constraint, or gate proposal
+  -> ClaimGate steering projection
+  -> host Lev consumption
+  -> AdmitFlow / receipt policy
+  -> accepted graph patch or rejected/requeued work
+```
+
+## Source Pattern Status
+
+The current useful source families are pattern inputs, not authority inputs:
+
+- `0xRicker self-verifying loop`: verify every output, reject failures, requeue
+  only failed items, stop on zero hard verifier failures.
+- `Ponytail`: minimality discipline; reject overbuilt patches and duplicate
+  proof paths.
+- `oh-my-openagent` / durable-team patterns: durable named work lanes and
+  artifacts, not proof by team output.
+- `Wizard v4.3`: object boundary, route truth, sequential council discipline,
+  and proxy-drift checks. Wizard output proposes and organizes work; it does
+  not promote canon.
+- Codex Ratchet: attractor-basin digging, axiom digging, constraint digging,
+  and gate digging.
+
+Each source may shape roles, branch lanes, and candidate gates. None may mark a
+projection as `live_lev_consumed`, `properly_integrated`,
+`release_admission_allowed`, or otherwise admitted by host Lev.
+
+## Loop Topologies
+
+There are two different loops and both are useful:
+
+| Loop | Purpose | Authority ceiling |
+| --- | --- | --- |
+| Branch / council / swarm loop | Generate many candidate attacks, repairs, gates, and counterexamples in parallel. | Proposal only. |
+| Gate / verify / requeue loop | Deterministically check work, reject failed items, requeue only failures, and stop on zero hard failures. | Can feed host admission when evidence is bound. |
+
+The swarm is the search field. The gate loop is the pruning wall. Only the
+pruned, receipt-bound result can enter host admission.
+
+## Host Consumption Rules
+
+Host Lev consumes ClaimGate steering projections from:
+
+```text
+.lev/steering/runs/<run-id>/
+  run.json
+  proof-spec.json
+  eval-job.json
+  eval-job-output.json
+  boundary.json
+```
+
+`consumeClaimGateSteeringRun` must:
+
+1. Require every file above.
+2. Check cross-file object binding.
+3. Recompute the verdict from `ProofResult[]` evidence.
+4. Reject verdict mismatch.
+5. Reject self-asserted host authority flags.
+6. Write host consumption receipts without mutating source projection files.
+
+The source projection can say what ClaimGate observed. Host Lev decides whether
+that observation was consumed.
+
+## Admission Boundary
+
+`AdmitFlow` remains the ratchet admission policy. A future
+`CodexRatchetAdmitFlow` must be a thin orchestration wrapper over existing host
+primitives, not a new proof stack:
+
+```text
+consumeClaimGateSteeringRun
+  -> EvalJobOutput
+  -> AdmitFlow.evaluate
+  -> Receipt
+```
+
+Promotion requires host evidence and ratchet policy. Axiom diggers, constraint
+diggers, gate diggers, Wizard councils, or source packs can propose candidates
+but cannot directly admit them.
+
+## Minimal Patch Rule
+
+Every bridge patch must answer:
+
+- What source pattern justified this?
+- Which host gate can reject it?
+- Which receipt proves it ran?
+- What claim ceiling applies?
+- What did it intentionally not add?
+
+If those answers are unclear, keep the work proposal-only and requeue it.
